
B1. Purpose
This appendix proposes a legislative framework for transitioning Alberta’s mental health system from a predominantly biomedical and institutional model toward relational, community-based care. The goal is not abrupt abolition, but a deliberate, phased shift that redirects the flow of resources toward approaches rooted in human relationship, cultural sovereignty, and lived reality.

B2. The Current Pattern
Despite substantial public investment, Alberta’s current mental health system has not produced proportional improvements in wellbeing. Rates of addiction, suicide, youth distress, and Indigenous mental health crises remain high or continue to rise. In Flow-Core terms, this reflects à without 出 — a system that gathers suffering into diagnostic categories and pharmaceutical solutions while resisting deeper structural release.
The human author of this document has personally witnessed the interior of psychiatric wards and has spoken at length with many individuals who live under the “mental illness” label this system claims to serve. One of the most consistent and damaging patterns is the abrupt discharge with little to no follow-up care. People are frequently released at a moment of extreme vulnerability, often with no meaningful transition plan. Their families and support networks are left completely outside the experience — unaware of what occurred inside the ward and unequipped to help the person reintegrate. The system forces a sudden, unsupported dissolution that leaves individuals and their relations to navigate the raw aftermath alone. This is not healing. It is another form of relational rupture.

B3. Principles for Transition
Flow-Core recommends a ten-year transition period that includes:
Strengthened informed consent standards for psychiatric medications, with full disclosure of risks including dependence, tolerance, and protracted withdrawal syndromes.
Publicly funded deprescribing pathways and peer-led support networks for those choosing to reduce or discontinue medication.
Significant expansion of community-based alternatives: peer respite centres, Soteria-style houses, Open Dialogue approaches, and Indigenous-led land-based recovery programs. These approaches are not hypothetical. Appendix F outlines a pilot-ready model for Indigenous-led restorative justice and community-based dispute resolution, drawing on decades of documented success in Māori Family Group Conferences and Navajo Peacemaker Courts. The same principles — relational dialogue, community accountability, and the redirection of professional resources into facilitation rather than enforcement — apply equally to mental health crisis response, where adversarial and carceral approaches have consistently failed.
Full recognition of Indigenous psychic sovereignty, with direct funding to Nations and communities to design and deliver care according to their own knowledge systems and governance.
Retention of acute care as short-term, last-resort options, with mandatory follow-up planning that actively includes the person's chosen support network before discharge. Funding should be made available to families and chosen networks providing this post-discharge relational support. This moves us away from the professionalization of care work and toward genuine community-held care, recognizing the significant emotional and practical labour already being done by those who love and know the person best.

B4. Impact on Children and the Need for Liberation
Children suffer greatly under the current psychiatric model of care. They are too often labeled, medicated, and institutionalized when families feel overwhelmed or unequipped to support them. These stories are not rare. The widely reported case of L.L. who died in foster care after being prescribed powerful psychiatric drugs intended for adults should be a wake up call. These examples illustrate how the current system can be used as a form of family abandonment or institutional control rather than genuine care.
This is why children’s liberation (see appendix C) is so deeply connected to mental health reform. When we pathologize and medicate children’s distress instead of addressing the relational, social, and material conditions around them, we reproduce the same cycles of rupture and containment that Alice Miller detailed in her revolutionary book For Your Own Good.

B5. Closing
The mental health system does not need to be destroyed. It needs to be invited back into the living cycle of gii-izhi-ayaad — to gather with humility, stabilize with care, and release with proper relational support so that healing can continue outside the walls of the institution.
This is not merely policy reform.  
It is an act of relational repair.
